---
import BlogPostLayout from '../layouts/BlogPostLayout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---

<BlogPostLayout
  title="Shipping Flutter to Desktop: what I wish I'd known"
  description="Expanding a mobile Flutter app to Windows and macOS surfaces a whole new set of challenges. Here's what to expect and how to handle it."
  canonicalUrl="https://waseemarain4u.github.io/my-portfolio/blog-article-desktop"
  ogImage="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1593642532454-e138e28a63f4?w=1200&q=80"
  tag="Flutter"
  date="Oct 5, 2024"
  readTime="7 min read"
>
  <p>Flutter's promise of "one codebase, every platform" is mostly true — until you try to actually ship to desktop. I've taken two Flutter apps to Windows and macOS, and the experience taught me a lot about where the gaps are between the pitch and the reality.</p>

  <h2>The layout assumptions break</h2>
  <p>Mobile layouts assume a narrow portrait screen. Desktop apps live in wide, resizable windows. Every hardcoded width, every full-screen dialog, every bottom sheet — they all look wrong on a 1400px wide window. Before starting a desktop port, I now audit the codebase for layout assumptions and plan a responsive pass.</p>
  <p>The <code>LayoutBuilder</code> and <code>MediaQuery</code> APIs give you the tools to handle this, but it requires deliberate design decisions. What should the sidebar look like? When should you show a master-detail layout instead of stacked navigation? These are design problems, not engineering ones — involve your designer early.</p>

  <h2>Input model is completely different</h2>
  <p>Mobile apps are built around touch. Desktop users have a mouse, keyboard shortcuts, right-click context menus, and hover states. None of this comes for free in Flutter.</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Add keyboard shortcuts with <code>Shortcuts</code> and <code>Actions</code> widgets</li>
    <li>Add hover states using <code>MouseRegion</code></li>
    <li>Add right-click menus with <code>GestureDetector</code> on secondary tap</li>
    <li>Make sure all interactive elements have appropriate cursor changes</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Skipping these doesn't break the app, but it makes it feel unfinished to desktop users.</p>

  <h2>Platform plugins are the biggest risk</h2>
  <p>Most Flutter plugins were written for Android and iOS. Desktop support was added later — and not always completely. Before committing to a desktop port, audit every plugin you use. Check the pub.dev page for Windows and macOS support badges. I've been burned by plugins that listed desktop support but had critical missing functionality on one platform.</p>
  <p>For plugins without desktop support, your options are: find an alternative, implement the platform channel yourself, or use a conditional import to stub the functionality on desktop.</p>

  <h2>Window management needs attention</h2>
  <p>Flutter desktop apps launch in a default window size that's often wrong for your app. Use the <code>window_manager</code> plugin to set a minimum size, remember window position across launches, and handle close events properly. These details separate a polished desktop app from a mobile app running in a window.</p>
  <p>The overall conclusion: Flutter desktop is genuinely production-ready in 2024, but the work to get there is mostly design and UX work, not engineering. Plan for an extra sprint to make the app feel native on each platform.</p>

  <div slot="more-articles">
    <section class="bg-zinc-50 dark:bg-zinc-900/40 py-16">
      <div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto px-6">
        <h2 class="font-display font-bold text-2xl text-zinc-900 dark:text-white mb-8">More articles</h2>
        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-6">
          {[
            { href: 'blog-article', img: 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1607252650355-f7fd0460ccdb?w=700&q=80', alt: 'Clean Architecture', date: 'May 10, 2025', title: 'Why I switched from MVC to Clean Architecture in Flutter' },
            { href: 'blog-article-performance', img: 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1461749280684-dccba630e2f6?w=700&q=80', alt: 'Performance', date: 'Dec 2, 2024', title: "5 Flutter performance mistakes I made so you don't have to" },
            { href: 'blog-article-bloc', img: 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1516321318423-f06f85e504b3?w=700&q=80', alt: 'State management', date: 'Feb 18, 2025', title: 'BLoC, Riverpod, or Provider? My honest take after 4 years' },
          ].map(p => (
            <article class="group bg-white dark:bg-zinc-900 rounded-2xl overflow-hidden border border-zinc-100 dark:border-zinc-800 hover:border-accent transition-all hover:-translate-y-1">
              <div class="pf w-full h-40"><img src={p.img} alt={p.alt} loading="lazy"></div>
              <div class="p-5">
                <p class="text-xs text-zinc-400 mb-2">{p.date}</p>
                <a href={`${base}${p.href}`}><h3 class="font-display font-bold text-base text-zinc-900 dark:text-white group-hover:text-accent transition-colors">{p.title}</h3></a>
              </div>
            </article>
          ))}
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>
</BlogPostLayout>
